                <head>No. 33<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On June 27 the Department of State released to the press a statement by Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName> in which he expressed regret
                    at the steps being taken by Iran which threatened to close down the Abadan
                    refinery. <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName> stated that he was
                    disappointed that the British proposal presented by <persName corresp="#p_JCD1"
                        >Jackson</persName> had been summarily rejected without study and expressed
                    his hope that Iran would reconsider and seek some formula that would avoid the
                    dangers inherent in its actions and permit the continued operation of the oil
                    industry. <pb facs="0103" n="77" xml:id="pg_77"/> For text of Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>’s statement, see Department
                    of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 9, 1951, pages 72–73.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
